import pandas as pd

# Load datasets
user_df = pd.read_csv('/content/user.csv')
tourism_df = pd.read_excel('/content/tourism_with_id.xlsx')
rating_df = pd.read_csv('/content/tourism_rating.csv')

# ===== Preliminary inspection =====
print("=== User Dataset Info ===")
print(user_df.info())
print("\nMissing values:\n", user_df.isnull().sum())
print("\nDuplicate rows:", user_df.duplicated().sum())

print("\n=== Tourism Dataset Info ===")
print(tourism_df.info())
print("\nMissing values:\n", tourism_df.isnull().sum())
print("\nDuplicate rows:", tourism_df.duplicated().sum())

print("\n=== Rating Dataset Info ===")
print(rating_df.info())
print("\nMissing values:\n", rating_df.isnull().sum())
print("\nDuplicate rows:", rating_df.duplicated().sum())

# ===== Remove duplicates =====
user_df.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)
tourism_df.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)
rating_df.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)

# ===== Remove anomalies =====
# Age cleaning (if column exists)
age_col = None
for col in user_df.columns:
    if col.lower() == 'age':
        age_col = col
        break

if age_col:
    user_df = user_df[(user_df[age_col] >= 0) & (user_df[age_col] <= 100)]

# Invalid coordinates
if 'Lat' in tourism_df.columns and 'Long' in tourism_df.columns:
    tourism_df = tourism_df[(tourism_df['Lat'].between(-90, 90)) &
                            (tourism_df['Long'].between(-180, 180))]

# ===== Outlier removal =====
# Price outliers
if 'Price' in tourism_df.columns:
    price_upper = tourism_df['Price'].quantile(0.99)
    tourism_df = tourism_df[tourism_df['Price'] <= price_upper]

# Rating outliers
rating_col = None
for col in rating_df.columns:
    if 'rating' in col.lower():
        rating_col = col
        break

if rating_col:
    rating_df = rating_df[(rating_df[rating_col] >= 0) & (rating_df[rating_col] <= 5)]

# Reset index
user_df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
tourism_df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
rating_df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

print("\n✅ Cleaning complete.")
print(f"User dataset: {user_df.shape}")
print(f"Tourism dataset: {tourism_df.shape}")
print(f"Rating dataset: {rating_df.shape}")

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# ---------- Helper to find matching column ----------
def find_col(df, target, contains=False):
    t = target.lower()
    for c in df.columns:
        if (not contains and c.lower() == t) or (contains and t in c.lower()):
            return c
    return None

# Ensure required key columns exist
user_id_col_r = find_col(rating_df, 'user_id') or 'user_id'
user_id_col_u = find_col(user_df, 'user_id') or 'user_id'
place_id_col_r = find_col(rating_df, 'place_id') or 'place_id'
place_id_col_t = find_col(tourism_df, 'place_id') or 'Place_id'
rating_col = find_col(rating_df, 'rating', contains=True) or 'place_rating'

# Merge ratings with users
ratings_users = rating_df.merge(
    user_df,
    left_on=user_id_col_r,
    right_on=user_id_col_u,
    how='inner'
)

# Detect age and location cols
age_col = find_col(ratings_users, 'age')
origin_loc_col = find_col(ratings_users, 'location', contains=True)

# ---------- 1) Age distribution ----------
if age_col and pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(ratings_users[age_col]):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    ratings_users[age_col].plot(kind='hist', bins=15)
    plt.title('Age Distribution of Tourists Giving Ratings')
    plt.xlabel('Age')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Tourists')
    plt.show()
else:
    print("⚠ No numeric age column found — skipping age distribution.")

# ---------- 2) Top origin locations ----------
if origin_loc_col:
    top_locations = ratings_users[origin_loc_col].value_counts().head(10)
    plt.figure(figsize=(9,6))
    top_locations[::-1].plot(kind='barh')
    plt.title('Top 10 Tourist Origin Locations')
    plt.xlabel('Number of Tourists')
    plt.ylabel('Origin Location')
    plt.show()
    display(top_locations.to_frame('count'))
else:
    print("⚠ No origin location column found — skipping.")

# ---------- 3) Age distribution by city ----------
city_col_t = find_col(tourism_df, 'city') or 'City'
merged_city = ratings_users.merge(
    tourism_df[[place_id_col_t, city_col_t]].dropna(),
    left_on=place_id_col_r,
    right_on=place_id_col_t,
    how='inner'
)

if age_col and city_col_t in merged_city.columns and pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(merged_city[age_col]):
    top_cities = merged_city[city_col_t].value_counts().head(5).index
    for city in top_cities:
        city_df = merged_city[merged_city[city_col_t] == city]
        plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
        city_df[age_col].plot(kind='hist', bins=12)
        plt.title(f'Age Distribution for Places in {city}')
        plt.xlabel('Age')
        plt.ylabel('Number of Tourists')
        plt.show()

# ---------- 4) Age distribution by category ----------
cat_col_t = find_col(tourism_df, 'category') or 'Category'
merged_cat = ratings_users.merge(
    tourism_df[[place_id_col_t, cat_col_t]].dropna(),
    left_on=place_id_col_r,
    right_on=place_id_col_t,
    how='inner'
)

if age_col and cat_col_t in merged_cat.columns and pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(merged_cat[age_col]):
    top_cats = merged_cat[cat_col_t].value_counts().head(5).index
    for cat in top_cats:
        cat_df = merged_cat[merged_cat[cat_col_t] == cat]
        plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
        cat_df[age_col].plot(kind='hist', bins=12)
        plt.title(f'Age Distribution for Category: {cat}')
        plt.xlabel('Age')
        plt.ylabel('Number of Tourists')
        plt.show()

# ============================================================
# Part 2 – Point 3 (I, II, III) with heatmaps + robust Nature logic
# ============================================================
import re
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns  # comment out if you don't want seaborn

# ---------- Helpers ----------
def find_col(df, target, contains=False):
    t = target.lower()
    for c in df.columns:
        if (not contains and c.lower() == t) or (contains and t in c.lower()):
            return c
    return None

def or_contains(series: pd.Series, terms):
    """Case-insensitive substring OR across a list of terms; no regex; safe on NaNs."""
    s = series.astype(str)
    mask = pd.Series(False, index=s.index)
    for t in terms:
        if not t:
            continue
        mask = mask | s.str.contains(t, case=False, na=False, regex=False)
    return mask

# ---------- Resolve column names (robust) ----------
place_id_col_t = find_col(tourism_df, 'place_id') or 'Place_id'
city_col_t     = find_col(tourism_df, 'city') or 'City'
cat_col_t      = find_col(tourism_df, 'category') or 'Category'

user_id_col_r  = find_col(rating_df, 'user_id') or 'user_id'
place_id_col_r = find_col(rating_df, 'place_id') or 'place_id'
rating_col     = find_col(rating_df, 'rating', contains=True) or 'place_rating'

# Optional lookup columns for smarter Nature matching
name_col = next((c for c in tourism_df.columns if c.lower() in ('place_name','name','title')), None)
desc_col = next((c for c in tourism_df.columns if 'desc' in c.lower()), None)

# ============================================================
# 3.I) What are the different categories of tourist spots?
# ============================================================
if cat_col_t in tourism_df.columns:
    categories = tourism_df[cat_col_t].dropna().unique()
    print("📌 Different categories of tourist spots (first 100 shown):")
    for c in sorted(categories)[:100]:
        print("-", c)
else:
    print("⚠ Category column not found in tourism data.")

# ============================================================
# 3.II) What kind of tourism each location is most famous/suitable for?
#       (A) by frequency (mode) and (B) by average rating
#       + Heatmaps: City × Category (counts & avg rating)
# ============================================================

# --- 3.II-A: By frequency (mode) ---
if city_col_t in tourism_df.columns and cat_col_t in tourism_df.columns:
    city_top_category_freq = (
        tourism_df.groupby(city_col_t)[cat_col_t]
        .agg(lambda x: x.value_counts().index[0])  # mode
        .reset_index()
        .rename(columns={cat_col_t: 'Most_Common_Category_By_Count'})
    )
    print("\n🏙 Most famous tourism type per city (by frequency):")
    display(city_top_category_freq)
else:
    print("⚠ Missing city/category columns for frequency view.")

# --- 3.II-B: By average rating ---
merged_for_ratings = tourism_df.merge(
    rating_df[[place_id_col_r, rating_col]],
    left_on=place_id_col_t,
    right_on=place_id_col_r,
    how='left'
)

if all(c in merged_for_ratings.columns for c in [city_col_t, cat_col_t, rating_col]) and merged_for_ratings[rating_col].notna().any():
    avg_rating_cc = (
        merged_for_ratings
        .groupby([city_col_t, cat_col_t], dropna=True)[rating_col].mean()
        .reset_index()
        .sort_values([city_col_t, rating_col], ascending=[True, False])
    )
    city_top_category_rating = (
        avg_rating_cc.groupby(city_col_t).head(1)
        .rename(columns={cat_col_t: 'Top_Category_By_Avg_Rating',
                         rating_col: 'Top_Category_AvgRating'})
        [[city_col_t, 'Top_Category_By_Avg_Rating', 'Top_Category_AvgRating']]
        .reset_index(drop=True)
    )
    print("\n⭐ Most famous tourism type per city (by average rating):")
    display(city_top_category_rating)
else:
    print("ℹ Not enough ratings to compute rating-based top categories.")

# --- Heatmap 1: City × Category counts (Top-K categories) ---
if cat_col_t in tourism_df.columns and city_col_t in tourism_df.columns:
    count_xtab = pd.crosstab(tourism_df[city_col_t], tourism_df[cat_col_t])
    K = 10  # show top K categories for readability
    top_cats = count_xtab.sum(axis=0).sort_values(ascending=False).head(K).index
    count_xtab_top = count_xtab[top_cats]

    plt.figure(figsize=(1.1*len(top_cats)+4, 1.1*len(count_xtab_top.index)+3))
    sns.heatmap(count_xtab_top, annot=False, fmt='g')
    plt.title('City vs Category — Spot Counts (Top Categories)')
    plt.xlabel('Category')
    plt.ylabel('City')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    print("\nCity × Category — Counts (Top Categories):")
    display(count_xtab_top)
else:
    print("⚠ Cannot build count heatmap (missing city/category columns).")

# --- Heatmap 2: City × Category average rating (aligned to Top-K if possible) ---
if rating_col in merged_for_ratings.columns and merged_for_ratings[rating_col].notna().any():
    avg_rating = (
        merged_for_ratings
        .groupby([city_col_t, cat_col_t], dropna=True)[rating_col].mean()
        .reset_index()
    )
    rating_pivot = avg_rating.pivot(index=city_col_t, columns=cat_col_t, values=rating_col)
    exist_top_cats = [c for c in (top_cats if 'top_cats' in locals() else rating_pivot.columns) if c in rating_pivot.columns]
    rating_pivot_top = rating_pivot[exist_top_cats] if exist_top_cats else rating_pivot

    plt.figure(figsize=(1.1*len(rating_pivot_top.columns)+4, 1.1*len(rating_pivot_top.index)+3))
    sns.heatmap(rating_pivot_top, annot=True, fmt=".2f")
    plt.title('City vs Category — Average Rating')
    plt.xlabel('Category')
    plt.ylabel('City')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    print("\nCity × Category — Average Rating:")
    display(rating_pivot_top)
else:
    print("ℹ No ratings available to compute rating heatmap.")

# ============================================================
# 3.III) Which city is best for a Nature enthusiast?
#       Robust dynamic detection WITHOUT regex warnings
#       Strategy: try Category → Place_name → Description → fallback inference
# ============================================================

# Seed substrings (no regex) — tune freely
seed_terms = [
    'nature','natural','outdoor','park','forest','waterfall','mountain','beach','lake',
    'garden','wildlife','reserve','eco','trail','hike','national','marine','island',
    'river','cave','geopark','botanical','zoo','safari','valley','spring','hill','green'
]

# A) Try matching in Category
mask_cat = or_contains(tourism_df[cat_col_t], seed_terms) if cat_col_t in tourism_df.columns else pd.Series(False, index=tourism_df.index)
# B) Try Place_name
mask_name = or_contains(tourism_df[name_col], seed_terms) if name_col else pd.Series(False, index=tourism_df.index)
# C) Try Description
mask_desc = or_contains(tourism_df[desc_col], seed_terms) if desc_col else pd.Series(False, index=tourism_df.index)

nature_mask = mask_cat | mask_name | mask_desc
nature_df = tourism_df[nature_mask].copy()

print("\nNature match summary:", {
    'matched_in_category': int(mask_cat.sum()) if isinstance(mask_cat, pd.Series) else 0,
    'matched_in_name': int(mask_name.sum()) if isinstance(mask_name, pd.Series) else 0,
    'matched_in_description': int(mask_desc.sum()) if isinstance(mask_desc, pd.Series) else 0,
    'total_unique_matches': len(nature_df)
})

# Fallback: if still nothing, infer likely nature categories by token overlap
if nature_df.empty and cat_col_t in tourism_df.columns:
    def tokenize(txt):
        return set(re.findall(r'[a-z]+', str(txt).lower()))
    seed_set = set(seed_terms)
    cat_scores = (
        tourism_df[cat_col_t]
        .dropna()
        .map(lambda x: len(tokenize(x) & seed_set))
        .to_frame('score')
        .join(tourism_df[[cat_col_t]], how='left')
    )
    guessed_cats = (
        cat_scores.groupby(cat_col_t)['score'].max()
        .sort_values(ascending=False)
    )
    guessed_cats = guessed_cats[guessed_cats > 0].head(5).index.tolist()
    if guessed_cats:
        print("Fallback guessed nature-like categories:", guessed_cats)
        nature_df = tourism_df[tourism_df[cat_col_t].isin(guessed_cats)].copy()

if len(nature_df):
    print("\nSample matched (nature-like) rows:")
    cols_to_show = [c for c in [cat_col_t, name_col, desc_col, city_col_t] if c]
    display(nature_df[cols_to_show].head(10))

    # Merge ratings to pick best cities by count & rating
    merged_nature = nature_df.merge(
        rating_df[[place_id_col_r, rating_col]],
        left_on=place_id_col_t,
        right_on=place_id_col_r,
        how='left'
    )

    top_city_count = merged_nature[city_col_t].value_counts().idxmax()

    if rating_col in merged_nature.columns and merged_nature[rating_col].notna().any():
        top_city_rating = (
            merged_nature.groupby(city_col_t)[rating_col]
            .mean()
            .sort_values(ascending=False)
            .index[0]
        )
    else:
        top_city_rating = None

    print("\n🌿 Best city for nature enthusiasts (robust detection):")
    print(f"- By count of nature-like spots: {top_city_count}")
    if top_city_rating:
        print(f"- By average rating of nature-like spots: {top_city_rating}")

    print("\nNature-like spots per city (Top 10):")
    display(merged_nature[city_col_t].value_counts().head(10).to_frame('count'))
else:
    print("🌿 No nature-like places identified. Consider mapping your categories to a standard taxonomy (e.g., map 'Parks & Recreation' → 'Nature').")

# ============================================================
# Part 2 – Step 4: Most Loved Spots / Cities / Categories
# ============================================================
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# ---------- Helper ----------
def find_col(df, target, contains=False):
    t = target.lower()
    for c in df.columns:
        if (not contains and c.lower() == t) or (contains and t in c.lower()):
            return c
    return None

def bayesian_average(avg, n, C, m):
    """Bayesian smoothing for small sample sizes."""
    return (m*C + n*avg) / (m + n)

# ---------- Resolve column names ----------
place_id_col_t = find_col(tourism_df, 'place_id') or 'Place_id'
name_col_t     = find_col(tourism_df, 'place_name') or (next((c for c in tourism_df.columns if c.lower() in ('name','title')), None))
city_col_t     = find_col(tourism_df, 'city') or 'City'
cat_col_t      = find_col(tourism_df, 'category') or 'Category'

place_id_col_r = find_col(rating_df, 'place_id') or 'place_id'
rating_col     = find_col(rating_df, 'rating', contains=True) or 'place_rating'

# ---------- Clean Category ----------
tourism_df[cat_col_t] = (
    tourism_df[cat_col_t]
    .astype(str)
    .str.strip()
    .replace({'': np.nan, 'nan': np.nan, 'None': np.nan})
    .str.title()
)

# ---------- Combine ratings with place info ----------
combined = rating_df.merge(
    tourism_df[[place_id_col_t, name_col_t, city_col_t, cat_col_t]],
    left_on=place_id_col_r, right_on=place_id_col_t, how='left'
)

# ---------- Global stats for smoothing ----------
global_mean = combined[rating_col].mean()
count_per_place = combined.groupby(place_id_col_t)[rating_col].count()
m_conf = int(np.clip(count_per_place.median() if len(count_per_place) else 10, 5, 20))

# ============================================================
# 4.I – Most Loved Spots + City with Most Loved Spots
# ============================================================
agg_place = (
    combined
    .groupby([place_id_col_t, name_col_t, city_col_t, cat_col_t], dropna=False)[rating_col]
    .agg(['count', 'mean'])
    .rename(columns={'count':'n_ratings','mean':'avg_rating'})
    .reset_index()
)

agg_place['bayes_score'] = bayesian_average(
    agg_place['avg_rating'], agg_place['n_ratings'], global_mean, m_conf
)

# Define top X% by Bayesian score
min_n = max(5, int(np.percentile(agg_place['n_ratings'], 25)))
top_pct = 10
cutoff = np.percentile(agg_place['bayes_score'], 100 - top_pct)

    agg_place[(agg_place['bayes_score'] >= cutoff) & (agg_place['n_ratings'] >= min_n)]
    .sort_values(['bayes_score','n_ratings','avg_rating'], ascending=[False, False, False])

# City with most loved spots

# ============================================================
# Part 2 – Step 5 (Surprise‑free): Collaborative Filtering
#   A) Item‑based CF (cosine; CSC mean‑centering + overlap + shrinkage)
#   B) Model‑based CF via TruncatedSVD (no scikit‑surprise needed)
#   Helpers:
#     - recommend_similar_places(place_name, top_n=10, min_overlap=5)
#     - recommend_for_user(user_id, top_n=10, filter_seen=True)
# ============================================================
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity
from sklearn.decomposition import TruncatedSVD
from scipy.sparse import csr_matrix

# ---------- Reuse helper ----------
def find_col(df, target, contains=False):
    t = target.lower()
    for c in df.columns:
        if (not contains and c.lower() == t) or (contains and t in c.lower()):
            return c
    return None

# ---------- Resolve column names ----------
place_id_col_t = find_col(tourism_df, 'place_id') or 'Place_id'
name_col_t     = find_col(tourism_df, 'place_name') or (next((c for c in tourism_df.columns if c.lower() in ('name','title')), None))
city_col_t     = find_col(tourism_df, 'city') or 'City'
cat_col_t      = find_col(tourism_df, 'category') or 'Category'

user_id_col_r  = find_col(rating_df, 'user_id') or 'user_id'
place_id_col_r = find_col(rating_df, 'place_id') or 'place_id'
rating_col     = find_col(rating_df, 'rating', contains=True) or 'place_rating'

# ---------- Build ID/name maps ----------
id_to_name = tourism_df.set_index(place_id_col_t)[name_col_t].to_dict() if name_col_t else {}
name_to_id = {v: k for k, v in id_to_name.items() if pd.notna(v)}

# ---------- Prepare ratings ----------
ratings = rating_df[[user_id_col_r, place_id_col_r, rating_col]].dropna()
ratings[rating_col] = pd.to_numeric(ratings[rating_col], errors='coerce')
ratings = ratings.dropna(subset=[rating_col])

# Contiguous indices
user_index = {u:i for i, u in enumerate(ratings[user_id_col_r].unique())}
item_index = {p:i for i, p in enumerate(ratings[place_id_col_r].unique())}
index_to_item = {i:p for p,i in item_index.items()}

rows = ratings[user_id_col_r].map(user_index).to_numpy()
cols = ratings[place_id_col_r].map(item_index).to_numpy()
data = ratings[rating_col].to_numpy(dtype=float)

# User×Item matrix (CSR)
R = csr_matrix((data, (rows, cols)), shape=(len(user_index), len(item_index)))

# ============================================================
# A) ITEM‑BASED CF (stable CSC column‑centering + overlap + shrinkage)
# ============================================================
# Column mean‑center in CSC
R_csc = R.tocsc(copy=True)
n_items = R_csc.shape[1]
item_means = np.zeros(n_items, dtype=float)
for j in range(n_items):
    s, e = R_csc.indptr[j], R_csc.indptr[j+1]
    if e > s:
        col_vals = R_csc.data[s:e]
        m = col_vals.mean()
        item_means[j] = m
        R_csc.data[s:e] = col_vals - m

# Cosine similarity on centered items (sparse)
item_sim = cosine_similarity(R_csc.T, dense_output=False)

# Overlap (common raters per pair)
R_bin = (R > 0).astype(int)
overlap = (R_bin.T @ R_bin)  # sparse item×item

def recommend_similar_places(place_name, top_n=10, min_overlap=5, shrinkage=10):
    """Similar places to a given place_name using item‑item cosine with overlap & shrinkage."""
    if not name_col_t:
        raise ValueError("Place name column not found in tourism_df.")
    if place_name not in name_to_id:
        print(f"'{place_name}' not found. Examples:", list(name_to_id.keys())[:10])
        return pd.DataFrame()
    pid = name_to_id[place_name]
    if pid not in item_index:
        print(f"No ratings for '{place_name}' yet (cold start).")
        return pd.DataFrame()

    j = item_index[pid]
    sims = item_sim.getrow(j).toarray().ravel()
    ovl  = overlap.getrow(j).toarray().ravel()

    sims[j] = 0.0
    ovl[j]  = 0

    mask = ovl >= min_overlap
    if not mask.any():
        mask = ovl > 0  # relax for small datasets

    shrunken = np.zeros_like(sims)
    valid = np.where(mask)[0]
    shrunken[valid] = sims[valid] * (ovl[valid] / (ovl[valid] + shrinkage))

    cand_idx = np.argsort(-shrunken)[: max(50, top_n*3)]
    out = []
    for idx in cand_idx:
        if shrunken[idx] <= 0:
            continue
        cand_pid = index_to_item[idx]
        out.append({
            'place_id': cand_pid,
            'place_name': id_to_name.get(cand_pid, str(cand_pid)),
            'similarity': float(shrunken[idx]),
            'overlap_users': int(ovl[idx]),
            'item_mean_rating': float(item_means[idx])
        })
        if len(out) >= top_n:
            break
    return pd.DataFrame(out)

# ============================================================
# B) MODEL‑BASED CF (TruncatedSVD) — Surprise‑free
#    Steps:
#      1) Row‑de‑mean users in CSR
#      2) Fit TruncatedSVD on de‑meaned R
#      3) Predict = user_mean + (U @ Vt) row for user
# ============================================================
# Row de‑mean
R_demean = R.copy().astype(float)
user_means = np.zeros(R.shape[0], dtype=float)
for i in range(R.shape[0]):
    s, e = R_demean.indptr[i], R_demean.indptr[i+1]
    if e > s:
        row_vals = R_demean.data[s:e]
        m = row_vals.mean()
        user_means[i] = m
        R_demean.data[s:e] = row_vals - m

# Fit SVD (components ~ latent factors)
n_components = min(50, max(2, min(R_demean.shape) - 1))  # keep it safe for small data
svd = TruncatedSVD(n_components=n_components, random_state=42)
U = svd.fit_transform(R_demean)        # users × k
Vt = svd.components_                   # k × items

# Pre‑compute full item score vector per user on demand
def recommend_for_user(user_id, top_n=10, filter_seen=True):
    """Personalized top‑N using TruncatedSVD (no external deps)."""
    if user_id not in user_index:
        print("Cold‑start user: no history found.")
        return pd.DataFrame()

    u_idx = user_index[user_id]
    # latent score for all items
    scores = U[u_idx, :] @ Vt
    # add back the user's mean to map toward rating scale
    scores = scores + user_means[u_idx]

    # filter already‑seen
    seen = set(ratings.loc[ratings[user_id_col_r] == user_id, place_id_col_r].map(item_index))
    cand = []
    for j in range(Vt.shape[1]):
        if filter_seen and j in seen:
            continue
        cand_pid = index_to_item[j]
        cand.append((cand_pid, float(scores[j])))

    if not cand:
        print("No unseen items to recommend for this user.")
        return pd.DataFrame()

    cand.sort(key=lambda x: -x[1])
    top = cand[:top_n]
    return pd.DataFrame({
        'place_id': [pid for pid, _ in top],
        'place_name': [id_to_name.get(pid, str(pid)) for pid, _ in top],
        'svd_score': [score for _, score in top],
    })

# ---------- Convenience wrapper ----------
def recommend_from_current_place(place_name, top_n=10, min_overlap=5):
    return recommend_similar_places(place_name, top_n=top_n, min_overlap=min_overlap)

# ---------- Quick smoke tests (uncomment to try) ----------
display(recommend_from_current_place("Keraton Surabaya", top_n=10))
display(recommend_for_user(user_id=list(user_index.keys())[0], top_n=10))

            return c
    return None

# Resolve columns (robust)

Summary - Part 2¶

Point 1 — Data Import & Cleaning¶

Imported user.csv, tourism_with_id.csv, and tourism_rating.csv.

Checked for missing values & duplicates; anomalies (e.g., impossible ages) were removed.

Point 2 — User Group Exploration¶

Age distribution shows the majority of ratings come from younger to mid-aged tourists.

Top visitor origins identified — revealing which cities contribute most to tourism activity.

Point 3 — Locations & Categories¶

Listed all distinct tourist spot categories.

Identified for each city the most frequent and highest-rated tourism type.

Best city for “nature enthusiasts” was chosen based on count and average rating of nature-like spots.

Point 4 — Combined Data & Loved Spots¶

Merged tourism details with ratings.

“Most loved” spot overall identified via Bayesian average to account for low-rating bias.

Determined city with the most loved spots and category most liked by users.

Point 5 — Recommendation System¶

Built item-based collaborative filtering using cosine similarity + shrinkage.

Built model-based collaborative filtering using Truncated SVD (Surprise-free).

Functions can suggest similar places from a current location or recommend for a specific user.
